<br>
Granted, there are a few buggy things, but overall, it's nothing worse than i've seen with EQ.<br>
<br>
The only crappy part i don't like (but understand) is when your grave gets looted by a thief. i was in a bog group doing skrells, and there was a player, named &quot;Thief&quot; even, who was doing nothing but lurking around waiting for us to die so he could rob our graves. Irritating, yes, but also makes you work that much harder at staying alive. The roleplay aspect of this is quite cool, IMO.<br>
<br>
Yes, you acquire money very quickly, but you also spend it very quickly as well. Repairing your equipment after deaths eats quite a bit, as does training skill and abilities. When you look at the big picture of the economy, it's actually quite balanced. The other interesting thing is that the players have a lot of power over the economy itself. When a guild builds a city, they set the prices their merchants pay for sellable loots, and the prices items are sold for. Building cities is a MAJOR money sink, there's no doubt about that. It seems like you're getting a ton of monies when you first start out, but when you look at the prices for setting up a city with all the necessary buildings and NPC's, it's easy to see how quickly all that money is going to disappear.<br>
<br>
i also like how much variation there is from PC to PC. Two PC's who started out as healers could end up being VERY VERY different from each other as they progress through levels.<br>
<br>
The other thing i really like is how the monsters tend to be clustered in certain areas. You really don't have to worry too much when you're out running around exploring, since there's not much that just wanders around looking for players to eat. Once you find a spot to camp, you start killing, and the monsters respawn very quickly, so there's never a shortage of mobs to pull. You'll never wear out a camp, because about 5 minutes after you kill something, it's respawned and waiting to die again. If you think you're going to die, just run away, and after a short distance, the monster gives up, and forgets about you; no scrambling for a zone line where a train might be waiting for you on the other side.<br>
<br>
i haven't made it to a high enough level with any toon to actually engage in the PVP aspect of the game yet, but i'm sure it's going to be quite interesting as well. The thing i like about that, is when you're slain by someone, their name gets put on your personal list of &quot;people who killed me,&quot; along with their guild, so you can then take up your revenge later when you're better prepared. It's sort of like an automatically updating enemies list, instead of a friends list.<br>
<br>
Overall, i really like it, but it's certainly NOT like EQ. i comparing the two would be like comparing apples to oranges. The only similarity i see is that they're both MMORPG's, but their mechanics and dynamics are totally different from each other, which is quite refreshing.<br>
<br>
